religion_desc: I was raised Southern Baptist, however, since approximately 12 years of age I have not attended church.
treatmentq_05: I was never really in recovery over the past year, however, I relapsed 'hard' after having an administrative discharge from a PHP program (that I had transitioned to from their residential program) in April 2020. I never really got back on my feet with recovery after that, however, I did admit to another residential program in October 2020.
treatmentq_07: I'd say I relapsed (beyond 'just' moderately restricting, which started the day I discharged from residential in November 2020) following Christmas Day. Since then, I have continuously eaten below my body's energy needs.
treatmentq_08: At this time, I believe recovery for me will consist of getting to and maintaining a low-end of normal range weight, likely still eating fairly restricted in terms of limiting 'junk' or 'fun' foods. What I imagine is that 'recovery' for me will look more like a functional eating disorder.
fof_sc10: I avoid all 'traditional' carbohydrates aside from one cereal I'll eat at breakfast because my dietitian insists I have breakfast, and I've also told myself I wouldn't completely cut out all carbohydrates ever again. I do not eat any bread, bread products, tortillas, rice, pasta, quinoa, fruit, starchy vegetables, etc.

edthoughts_07: If I eat 'true' carbohydrates my weight will increase quickly.
edthoughts_09: If I gain weight the world (work, friends, society) will view me as lazy and incapable.
edthoughts_11: I am not thin enough for anyone to know I have an eating disorder, let alone anorexia.
edthoughts_13: I need to disinfect the kitchen (surfaces and handles) before I can prepare a meal or snack. This will prevent calories from foods other people have touched prior to touching the previously stated surfaces from 'contaminating' my food.
edthoughts_15: If I get to a so-called 'normal weight range' I will resume the binge eating behaviors that caused such significant weight gain years ago.
edthoughts_17: As my weight gets higher, my suicidal ideations become more intense and more difficult to brush off.
edthoughts_19: The eating disorder provides a sense of safety because it keeps my world small.
